1
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:35,560
And on that point,
members of the jury,...

2
00:00:35,680 --> 00:00:37,671
...I rest my case.

3
00:00:56,360 --> 00:00:59,113
[Camera shutter clicks]

4
00:01:02,200 --> 00:01:03,553
[Alarm clock rings]

5
00:01:29,360 --> 00:01:31,316
Hello, Wanda.

6
00:02:40,760 --> 00:02:42,113
Hi, Ken.

7
00:02:42,240 --> 00:02:43,389
Hello, W-W-Wanda.

8
00:02:44,360 --> 00:02:45,713
Ken,...

9
00:02:46,640 --> 00:02:47,595
...this is Otto.

10
00:02:47,720 --> 00:02:50,234
Hello, Ken.
Wanda's told me a lot about you.

11
00:02:50,360 --> 00:02:51,475
Hey! Great fish!

12
00:02:52,680 --> 00:02:55,717
A squeeze of lemon,
some tartare sauce... perfect!

13
00:02:56,640 --> 00:02:58,312
George back yet?

14
00:02:58,440 --> 00:03:00,351
No, he had to g-g-go...

15
00:03:00,480 --> 00:03:02,710
...to the b-b-b...

16
00:03:05,360 --> 00:03:06,395
What?

17
00:03:06,520 --> 00:03:09,956
That's quite a stutter
you've got there, Ken.

18
00:03:10,080 --> 00:03:12,674
[Laughs]
It's all right, it doesn't bother me.

19
00:03:12,800 --> 00:03:15,394
So er...
George needs a weapons man, eh?

20
00:03:16,360 --> 00:03:17,315
A cup of tea, Ken?

21
00:03:17,440 --> 00:03:19,237
Y-y-y...

22
00:03:19,360 --> 00:03:20,918
Yeah, he'd like one.

23
00:03:21,040 --> 00:03:23,600
I had a good friend
in the CIA, had a stutter.

24
00:03:23,720 --> 00:03:25,233
Cost him his life, dammit.

25
00:03:25,360 --> 00:03:26,793
[Door opens]

26
00:03:28,360 --> 00:03:30,112
Hi, George.

27
00:03:31,360 --> 00:03:33,157
Hello, George.

28
00:03:33,280 --> 00:03:34,349
Get you a Scotch?

29
00:03:34,480 --> 00:03:36,038
Yeah.

30
00:03:36,160 --> 00:03:37,115
George,...

31
00:03:38,360 --> 00:03:39,713
...this is Otto.

32
00:03:40,920 --> 00:03:42,273
So,...

33
00:03:42,400 --> 00:03:44,072
...you're Wanda's brother?

34
00:03:44,200 --> 00:03:45,599
Good to be here, George.

35
00:03:45,720 --> 00:03:47,438
England is a fine country.

36
00:03:47,560 --> 00:03:49,312
Did she tell you what we need?

37
00:03:54,360 --> 00:03:55,315
[Ken gasps]

38
00:03:58,160 --> 00:03:59,912
Something like that?

39
00:04:02,360 --> 00:04:04,316
Something like that.

40
00:04:05,960 --> 00:04:07,313
Hello, Wendy.

41
00:04:09,760 --> 00:04:10,954
Had a good day?

42
00:04:11,800 --> 00:04:14,951
I spend the morning trying
to get a waste disposal man.

43
00:04:15,080 --> 00:04:18,390
At lunch, Marjorie just
complained about her husband...

44
00:04:18,520 --> 00:04:21,353
...then I have to play
three rubbers with Philippa.

45
00:04:21,480 --> 00:04:24,278
I come back and Sandersons
have sent the wrong flowers.

46
00:04:24,400 --> 00:04:25,913
Oh, no!

47
00:04:27,200 --> 00:04:28,758
Would you like some tea?

48
00:04:29,760 --> 00:04:30,954
Yes.

49
00:04:32,160 --> 00:04:33,639
I won the case.

50
00:04:33,760 --> 00:04:37,070
This is the first moment
I've had to myself all day.

51
00:04:40,440 --> 00:04:42,317
Hello, Portia! How was the show?

52
00:04:42,440 --> 00:04:44,635
Awful, Daddy.
I must have a new horse.

53
00:04:44,760 --> 00:04:47,718
- But you liked Phantom.
- He's not fit for dog meat.

54
00:04:47,840 --> 00:04:49,910
Can I change him? It won't cost much.

55
00:04:50,040 --> 00:04:52,508
- Oughtn't we...
- I thought you were making tea.

56
00:04:52,640 --> 00:04:55,074
- I am, darling. Sorry.
- I'd better get it.

57
00:04:55,200 --> 00:04:57,430
- No, no, let me do it.
- No! I'll do it!

58
00:05:00,560 --> 00:05:01,913
I won the case.

59
00:05:02,040 --> 00:05:04,076
Now this is cracked.

60
00:05:05,560 --> 00:05:08,472
They're worth about 100,000 each.

61
00:05:08,960 --> 00:05:10,712
There are 135 of them.

62
00:05:10,840 --> 00:05:13,308
That makes 13 millions, my friends.

63
00:05:13,440 --> 00:05:14,555
Dollars or pounds?

64
00:05:14,680 --> 00:05:15,635
Pounds, pet.

65
00:05:15,760 --> 00:05:17,512
This is the big one. So...

66
00:05:19,760 --> 00:05:21,637
OK.

67
00:05:21,760 --> 00:05:23,830
Yeah.

68
00:05:23,960 --> 00:05:25,837
Otto?

69
00:05:25,960 --> 00:05:27,188
Yes?

70
00:05:27,320 --> 00:05:28,548
OK?

71
00:05:28,680 --> 00:05:29,635
What?

72
00:05:29,760 --> 00:05:30,875
The plan.

73
00:05:31,360 --> 00:05:32,998
Yeah. Great. No problem.

74
00:05:33,720 --> 00:05:36,439
What was the middle thing,
about the police?

75
00:05:37,720 --> 00:05:40,553
We don't meet up at
Heathrow until Tuesday...

76
00:05:40,680 --> 00:05:41,192
Yeah, yeah!

77
00:05:41,320 --> 00:05:43,151
I haven't finished yet.

78
00:05:43,280 --> 00:05:46,955
Because the police will watch
all the airports for 72 hours.

79
00:05:47,080 --> 00:05:47,956
I know.

80
00:05:48,080 --> 00:05:49,035
I know.

81
00:05:50,240 --> 00:05:52,708
Do you want me to g-g-get...

82
00:05:52,840 --> 00:05:55,115
...a b-b-big...

83
00:05:55,240 --> 00:05:58,198
...c-c-car?

84
00:05:58,320 --> 00:05:59,639
Getaway?

85
00:05:59,760 --> 00:06:01,113
A limo, OK?

86
00:06:01,240 --> 00:06:03,196
And put diplomatic plates on it.

87
00:06:03,320 --> 00:06:05,629
What if he has to
speak in the break-in?

88
00:06:05,760 --> 00:06:08,194
Nobody says anything
during a break-in.

89
00:06:08,320 --> 00:06:09,912
It's OK, Otto. Ken's good.

90
00:06:11,360 --> 00:06:13,316
So, next week,...

91
00:06:13,440 --> 00:06:15,396
...we won't have to look for work.

92
00:06:15,520 --> 00:06:17,511
And it won't have to look for us.

93
00:06:18,560 --> 00:06:20,516
Oscar Wilde.

94
00:06:24,880 --> 00:06:27,348
You really like animals,
don't you, Ken?

95
00:06:27,480 --> 00:06:29,152
What's the attraction?

96
00:06:29,280 --> 00:06:30,872
Because you can t-t-t...

97
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:34,310
...trust them, and
they don't sh-sh-sh...

98
00:06:34,440 --> 00:06:35,509
Shit on you?

99
00:06:35,640 --> 00:06:37,949
Show off all the time.

100
00:06:38,080 --> 00:06:40,389
You know what Nietzsche
said about them?

101
00:06:40,520 --> 00:06:42,909
He said they were
God's second blunder.

102
00:06:43,040 --> 00:06:44,189
Bye, sis!

103
00:06:44,680 --> 00:06:48,070
Well, you tell him
from me that I-I-I...

104
00:06:48,880 --> 00:06:50,108
Bye, George.

105
00:06:50,960 --> 00:06:53,315
If you talk to Mom,
tell her I said hi.

106
00:06:53,440 --> 00:06:55,396
- OK.
- (Don't let him touch you.)

107
00:06:55,520 --> 00:06:57,556
One more day, and we're together.

108
00:07:00,600 --> 00:07:02,636
I'm sorry about my brother, Ken.

109
00:07:02,760 --> 00:07:04,273
I know he's insensitive.

110
00:07:05,160 --> 00:07:06,798
He's had a hard life.

111
00:07:06,920 --> 00:07:08,273
Dad used to beat him up.

112
00:07:12,360 --> 00:07:13,873
Good.

113
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:14,955
Aaagh!

114
00:07:15,240 --> 00:07:17,231
[Screaming]

115
00:08:35,360 --> 00:08:37,316
Anybody moves and you're dead.

116
00:08:58,200 --> 00:09:00,236
[Alarm rings]

117
00:09:04,280 --> 00:09:06,236
[Dogs yap]

118
00:09:07,360 --> 00:09:09,237
Look where you're going!

119
00:09:09,360 --> 00:09:10,918
Chauvinist pig!

120
00:09:11,040 --> 00:09:14,350
Really, people here just
think they own the pavement.

121
00:09:17,400 --> 00:09:18,594
[Engine starts]

122
00:09:22,280 --> 00:09:24,350
[Brakes screech]

123
00:09:41,360 --> 00:09:42,509
That was fun.

124
00:09:42,640 --> 00:09:44,278
I love robbing the English.

125
00:09:44,400 --> 00:09:46,436
- They're so polite.
- The d-d-d...

126
00:09:46,560 --> 00:09:48,118
- What is it, Ken?
- The dog!

127
00:09:48,240 --> 00:09:49,468
We didn't hit the dog.

128
00:09:49,600 --> 00:09:53,229
- $20 million and an insect worries him!
- It's not an in-in...

129
00:09:53,360 --> 00:09:56,511
Stutter's not getting any better.
How about surgery?

130
00:09:56,640 --> 00:09:57,595
Shut up!

131
00:09:57,720 --> 00:09:59,039
[Siren]

132
00:10:03,440 --> 00:10:04,714
Ken.

133
00:10:06,360 --> 00:10:07,315
Bye!

134
00:10:37,760 --> 00:10:38,875
Let's split.

135
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:42,436
- See you at Heathrow on Tuesday.
- Lie low. No celebrating.

136
00:10:42,560 --> 00:10:43,993
No celebrating?

137
00:10:44,760 --> 00:10:46,352
See you in a couple of hours.

138
00:11:33,840 --> 00:11:34,989
To $20 million.

139
00:11:35,120 --> 00:11:36,189
To a job well done.

140
00:11:36,320 --> 00:11:37,275
To us.

141
00:11:37,400 --> 00:11:40,119
To the best brother and
sister team since...

142
00:11:40,240 --> 00:11:41,309
Romeo and Juliet?

143
00:11:41,760 --> 00:11:45,116
Do you believe those Cockney
klutzes bought our story?

144
00:11:45,240 --> 00:11:46,195
What morons!

145
00:11:46,320 --> 00:11:48,550
- I want you to know something.
- What?

146
00:11:48,680 --> 00:11:51,990
Even if you were my brother,
I'd still want to fuck you.

147
00:11:52,120 --> 00:11:53,075
Oooh!

148
00:11:54,760 --> 00:11:56,239
Make the call.

149
00:11:56,360 --> 00:11:57,918
- Momento, carissima.
- No!

150
00:11:58,040 --> 00:11:59,553
- Eventuale!
- No Italian!

151
00:11:59,680 --> 00:12:00,635
Hey!

152
00:12:00,760 --> 00:12:03,957
Per cominciare, due
insalate verdi con peperoni.

153
00:12:04,080 --> 00:12:06,548
- E linguine primavera...
- No. No.

154
00:12:06,680 --> 00:12:09,717
- Una cotoletta di vitello.
- Make the call, Otto.

155
00:12:09,840 --> 00:12:11,273
Are you really ltalian?

156
00:12:11,400 --> 00:12:12,879
Absolutamente. Si!

157
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:14,797
My name is Otto. It means eight.

158
00:12:14,920 --> 00:12:16,512
Say arrivederci a Giorgio.

159
00:12:16,640 --> 00:12:17,550
Bye, George.

160
00:12:17,680 --> 00:12:19,591
[Italian accent]
The police, please.

161
00:12:19,720 --> 00:12:21,312
Otto!

162
00:12:22,360 --> 00:12:24,237
[English accent]
Yes, hello.

163
00:12:24,360 --> 00:12:27,318
Sorry to trouble you, but
you may like to know...

164
00:12:27,440 --> 00:12:32,468
...that today's Hatton Garden robbery
was pulled off by Mr George Thomason.

165
00:12:32,600 --> 00:12:36,115
He lives at flat three,
Kipling Mansions,...

166
00:12:36,240 --> 00:12:39,550
...Murray Road, London W9.

167
00:12:40,320 --> 00:12:41,469
Wanda!

168
00:12:51,840 --> 00:12:53,796
[Siren]

169
00:13:03,760 --> 00:13:06,035
[Banging on door]
Police! Open up!

170
00:13:06,920 --> 00:13:08,558
Come on, open up!

171
00:13:12,800 --> 00:13:15,268
Open the door, or
we'll knock it down!

172
00:13:25,120 --> 00:13:26,872
George Francis Thomason?

173
00:13:38,560 --> 00:13:39,913
Passport,...

174
00:13:40,040 --> 00:13:41,189
...tickets,...

175
00:13:41,320 --> 00:13:42,275
...money!

176
00:13:46,760 --> 00:13:48,113
[Honks horn]

177
00:13:48,240 --> 00:13:49,878
Asshole!

178
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:51,638
[Crashing]

179
00:13:59,520 --> 00:14:01,112
We're rich, Wanda.

180
00:14:01,240 --> 00:14:02,309
Yep?

181
00:14:02,440 --> 00:14:04,078
I bet these weeks with me...

182
00:14:04,200 --> 00:14:07,078
...have been the most exciting
weeks of your life.

183
00:14:07,200 --> 00:14:08,349
You said it.

184
00:14:18,200 --> 00:14:20,191
[Breathes deeply]

185
00:14:20,760 --> 00:14:21,715
[Calmly]
OK.

186
00:14:22,360 --> 00:14:24,112
OK.

187
00:14:24,240 --> 00:14:25,719
Disappointed!

188
00:14:27,160 --> 00:14:28,513
Son of a bitch!

189
00:14:29,360 --> 00:14:31,920
What do you have to do to
make people trust you?!

190
00:14:32,040 --> 00:14:33,314
Shut up.

191
00:14:33,440 --> 00:14:36,000
People are always
taking advantage of me!

192
00:14:36,120 --> 00:14:38,315
Shut up and think.
Where's he moved it?

193
00:14:41,160 --> 00:14:42,149
What are you doing?

194
00:14:42,280 --> 00:14:44,236
I'm thinking!

195
00:14:44,360 --> 00:14:46,112
Thinking what I'll do to him.

196
00:14:46,240 --> 00:14:48,276
I'll hang him up
with piano wire...

197
00:14:48,400 --> 00:14:51,358
- Where are you going?
- I'm going to talk to him.

198
00:14:52,160 --> 00:14:53,309
Talk to who?

199
00:14:53,760 --> 00:14:54,875
Talk to who?!

200
00:14:55,000 --> 00:14:57,833
So, while installing
these windows,...

201
00:14:57,960 --> 00:15:01,589
...you knelt on some broken glass
from the pane you had dropped.

202
00:15:01,720 --> 00:15:02,869
That's right, sir.

203
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:04,877
Your parents can confirm this?

204
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:06,274
Yes, and his aunt,...

205
00:15:06,400 --> 00:15:07,913
...Georgina Thomason.

206
00:15:08,040 --> 00:15:09,029
Good, Bartlett.

207
00:15:09,160 --> 00:15:10,513
- [Knock at door]
- Yes?

208
00:15:11,280 --> 00:15:13,032
Sorry to interrupt you, sir.

209
00:15:13,160 --> 00:15:15,230
Thomason.
A young lady to see you.

210
00:15:15,360 --> 00:15:18,591
- Anything else?
- No, thanks. Do you have to dash off?

211
00:15:18,720 --> 00:15:20,039
No, absolutely not.

212
00:15:20,160 --> 00:15:21,115
George!

213
00:15:21,240 --> 00:15:23,800
Ken's got the fish food.
He'll be in later.

214
00:15:23,920 --> 00:15:25,069
- Thanks.
- De nada.

215
00:15:25,200 --> 00:15:26,872
What do you think, Mr Leach?

216
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:30,993
We may be OK on the glass, but
what else will they come up with?

217
00:15:35,160 --> 00:15:36,229
[Wolf whistling]

218
00:15:41,320 --> 00:15:43,072
Oh, George!

219
00:15:43,200 --> 00:15:45,919
Oh, my God, I can't believe
this is happening.

220
00:15:46,040 --> 00:15:47,951
That's not allowed in here, miss.

221
00:15:48,080 --> 00:15:49,229
Are you OK?

222
00:15:49,360 --> 00:15:50,509
It's all right.

223
00:15:50,640 --> 00:15:52,517
I don't think I can handle this.

224
00:15:52,640 --> 00:15:54,995
I was too afraid to
sleep last night...

225
00:15:55,120 --> 00:15:56,917
Leave it out, leave it out, OK?

226
00:15:57,960 --> 00:15:59,678
Listen, listen, listen.

227
00:15:59,800 --> 00:16:01,279
Listen.

228
00:16:02,360 --> 00:16:04,316
You stayed at my place.

229
00:16:05,360 --> 00:16:07,271
We slept late.

230
00:16:07,400 --> 00:16:09,356
You made me breakfast.

231
00:16:13,560 --> 00:16:15,312
What?

232
00:16:15,440 --> 00:16:17,317
What's he doing here?

233
00:16:17,440 --> 00:16:19,317
He wanted to see you.

234
00:16:19,960 --> 00:16:22,076
Who did it, George?
Kevin Delaney?

235
00:16:22,200 --> 00:16:24,156
Do you want me to rub him out?

236
00:16:24,280 --> 00:16:26,236
Anything, you name it.

237
00:16:26,360 --> 00:16:28,635
I have friends making enquiries.

238
00:16:28,760 --> 00:16:30,318
Good.

239
00:16:30,440 --> 00:16:33,034
The jewels are very safe.

240
00:16:33,160 --> 00:16:36,869
If I get sent down, it all gets
handed back to cut my sentence.

241
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:39,275
Now, to cut my sentence
even more,...

242
00:16:39,400 --> 00:16:41,755
...I could tell them
who done it with me...

243
00:16:41,880 --> 00:16:44,519
...if I wasn't very
happy about everything.

244
00:16:46,280 --> 00:16:48,077
What was the middle thing?

245
00:16:48,200 --> 00:16:50,156
Piss off.

246
00:16:53,760 --> 00:16:56,115
- You want me to spring you...
- Now!

247
00:17:01,160 --> 00:17:02,513
George?

248
00:17:03,760 --> 00:17:05,318
You don't think...

249
00:17:05,440 --> 00:17:06,998
Do you?

250
00:17:07,120 --> 00:17:08,075
No!

251
00:17:11,320 --> 00:17:12,275
No.

252
00:17:13,160 --> 00:17:14,434
No!

253
00:17:14,560 --> 00:17:16,357
OK.

254
00:17:16,480 --> 00:17:17,469
- George.
- What?

255
00:17:19,520 --> 00:17:21,954
Are you sure the garage
is very safe?

256
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:25,718
Trust me.

257
00:17:25,840 --> 00:17:27,592
Thank you very much.

258
00:17:27,720 --> 00:17:29,233
Thanks a lot. Bye.

259
00:17:29,360 --> 00:17:30,509
Have a good day.

260
00:17:31,600 --> 00:17:32,555
So?

261
00:17:32,680 --> 00:17:34,079
He's not sure it was you.

262
00:17:34,200 --> 00:17:35,155
What about you?

263
00:17:35,280 --> 00:17:36,633
No, no, he believes me.

264
00:17:36,760 --> 00:17:39,115
That's why he can't
figure out about you.

265
00:17:39,240 --> 00:17:40,229
Figure out what?

266
00:17:40,360 --> 00:17:42,828
Whether you turned him
in or not, stupid!

267
00:17:43,760 --> 00:17:45,716
Don't er...

268
00:17:45,840 --> 00:17:48,513
...ever, ever, ever...

269
00:17:48,640 --> 00:17:50,232
...call me stupid. OK?

270
00:17:52,680 --> 00:17:53,635
What?

271
00:17:57,240 --> 00:17:58,878
That's George's lawyer.

272
00:17:59,760 --> 00:18:01,955
The other guy must
be the barrister.

273
00:18:03,720 --> 00:18:04,675
So?

274
00:18:04,800 --> 00:18:05,915
Trust me.

275
